Merge pull request #1087 from stripe/matthewling-fix-upcoming-invoice-line-items Fix retrieval of upcoming Invoice line items

Fix retrieval of upcoming Invoice line items Some endpoints receive the "root" object id as a query string parameter for example

`/v1/invoices/upcoming/lines?customer=cus_xxx`

if `invoice.getLines().list(linesParams)` is used. If, in `linesParams`, further
options are passed (limit: 5 for example), these are incorrectly appended to
the URI using a question mark and not an ampersand, resulting in calls
for upcoming line items for a customer specified by a resource ID of cus_xxx?limit=5.

* `StringUtils` class & better API key validation (#928)

* Remove support for custom `URLStreamHandler` (#927)

* Refactor HTTP headers handling (#931)

* Add `CaseInsensitiveMap` class

* Add `HttpHeaders` class

* Use `HttpHeaders` in `StripeRequest`

* Use `HttpHeaders` in `StripeResponse`

* Address review comments

* Modernize `StripeResponse` (#932)

* Add `maxNetworkRetries` as a global and per-request setting (#934)

* Add `StreamUtils` class (#935)

* Remove support for `count` and `total_count` in list objects (#936)

* Codegen for openapi e07de1a (#938)

* Update README (#939)

Merge pull request #406 from stripe/brandur-dont-force-limitless-dns-cache Only set value on DNS cache TTL if it's been modified

Only set value on DNS cache TTL if it's been modified While making a request, stripe-java sets the DNS cache's TTL to zero. I
traced the commit back to 01fd2dba2ec1885f68c52355813eece3975ba3f1, but
unfortunately the author didn't leave us a shred of information as to
why they did this. I'd guess that it was was done because people were
setting long cache times and had originally resolved the host
incorrectly. I don't think it's related to security, because your TLS
certificate validation will still be active even if an attacker managed
to poison the DNS cache.

Here we take svilenivanovsmule's suggestion in #405 and only modify the
cache TTL *if* the user has overridden it. Java has pretty reasonable
defaults for this, and we shouldn't really need to touch it (unless
someone can think of a good reason why we would).

I think another very plausible option here is to just strip out all of
this code completely -- even someone who's written Java for only about
four minutes should've been able to tell that this code is not even
remotely thread-safe as written. Given that fact and no known reason why
this should be here, taking it out might be the right way to go.

Fixes #405.

Merge pull request #294 from stripe/brandur-remove-stripe-api-resource-collection Remove StripeAPIResourceCollection

Remove StripeAPIResourceCollection The current implementation has two collection implementations:

* `StripeAPIResourceCollection`: Extends `APIResource`; used when a
  collection needs access to either `request` or `requestCollection`.
* `StripeAPICollection`: Used in all other situations.

The two collection implementations are functionally identical except for
their parent class. This is somewhat error prone because as seen in #292,
it's easy to add something to one and forget about the other.

This pull eliminates `StripeAPIResourceCollection` and moves all
collections over to just extend `StripeCollection`, solving the
duplication problem and reducing code complexity.

The downside is that I've moved visibility of `request` and
`requestCollection` on `APIResource` to public so that they can be
called into from collection classes. It would be better if these had
something like `internal` visibility (a la C#), but Java doesn't really
support anything like that. IMO, it's still a reasonable trade-off and
we should still consider those `request*` methods "effectively" private
to the package and not part of the public API.

Fixes #292.

Merge pull request #275 from stripe/brandur-simple-options-overrides Allow request params and options to be overridden on `autoPagingIterator`

Allow request params and options to be overridden on `autoPagingIterator` We normally pass params and options with the `list` method:

    invoices = Invoice.list(params, options).autoPagingIterable()

This patch adds support for them to also be overridden from
`autoPagingIterator`:

    invoices = Invoice.list().autoPagingIterable(params, options)

The reason for this is to support custom params and options for
subcollections, which unfortunately do not inherit options from their
parent collections. For example:

    lineItems = invoice.getLines().autoPagingIterable(params, options)

There's more context for this in #264, and I tried a more elegant
solution (which failed) in #269. This seems like the easiest option for
the time being, with the possibility that we could do something more
sophisticated later to start consolidating our interfaces.

Fixes #264.

Detect support for TLSv1.1 and TLSv1.2 and only enable when supported Sufficiently old JREs might not support TLSv1.1 or 1.2 at all, which
is pretty unfortunate, but we should probably do better than just
crashing with an `IllegalArgumentException`.

In local testing, this also seems to fix the mysterious "Not enough
data to fill declared vector size" exception.  At a guess, enabling
TLSv1.2 but not TLSv1.1 confuses the handshake code.
Release 1.35.0

Manually enable TLSv1.2 for the benefit of Java 6 and 7 Java 6 and 7 both support TLSv1.2, but don't enable it (or TLSv1.1) by
default for TLS connections due to concerns at release-time around
server compatibility. At this point, those are largely addressed, and
TLSv1.0 is being deprecated by, among others, the PCI DSS within the
next year.

We don't want to pin specifically to TLSv1.2, as that makes us not
forward-compatible when TLSv1.3 (and later) is eventually
released. However, the only way I could find to update the list of
protocol versions was to call the setEnabledProtocols method on an
SSLSocket.

And the only way I could find to do that was to provide my own
SSLSocketFactory to HttpsURLConnection, which this does. The new
factory accepts an "underlying" factory as an argument, and proxies
all calls to it, enabling TLSv1.2 on the resulting sockets as
appropriate.

Adding support for posting multipart/form data and file uploads. This commit does a number of things in order to allow file uploads to be
included in the java bindings. These are:

1. It allows subclasses of APIResource to specify apiBase when
constructing a URL. This allows a method to point to base endpoints
different than `https://api.stripe.com`.

2. The multipartRequest method in APIResource allows one to post
multipart/form-data. To send a file, one simply needs to pass a
java.io.File as a value in params.

3. Creates the FileUpload resource which can be used to create and
retrieve file uploads from the Stripe upload API.

We're also bumping the version since this introduces changes into the
APIResource class.

Merge pull request #75 from marschall/volatile Statics in Stripe must be volatile

Statics in Stripe must be volatile According to the [Java Memory Model](http://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se7/html/jls-17.html#jls-17.4)
writes to a shared variable from one thread are only visible to an
other thread if there is a happens-before relationship between them.
There currently is no happens-before relationship between the writes
to `Stripe` `apiKey`, `apiVersion`, `apiBase` and the reads in
`APIResource`. There are several ways to introduce a happens-before
relationship between the writes and the reads but the easiest is to
mark the fields volatile.
